We've found that many large businesses have found that to be a very lucrative and profitable thing for them to be doing in our region.

1293
01:46:29,295 --> 01:46:38,865
But I would want Paul Moki to confirm whether what they are proposing qualifies under the rehabilitation portion of that ordinance.

1294
01:46:39,668 --> 01:46:40,088
Okay, thank you.

1295
01:46:40,128 --> 01:46:44,091
I mean, I would hope that $40 million counts as substantial rehabilitation.

1296
01:46:44,691 --> 01:46:53,896
So I'm just curious to Mr. Modica, is this $40 million inclusive of potentially a solar array, should it be deemed possible?

1297
01:46:53,976 --> 01:47:01,681
Or are there any other sustainability improvements that are included in this proposed $40 million rehabilitation?

1298
01:47:03,320 --> 01:47:04,961
I'm, I'm not aware.

1299
01:47:05,221 --> 01:47:10,522
I'm not aware of any specific solar modifications planned for this.

1300
01:47:10,643 --> 01:47:14,464
We're in our final construction forecasting.

1301
01:47:14,504 --> 01:47:19,406
No work has started obviously because there's approvals not been granted at this point.

1302
01:47:19,446 --> 01:47:25,128
So I can't answer if there's been any specific, I will tell you the monogram foods is a very green conscious company.

1303
01:47:26,008 --> 01:47:29,169
In our other eight facilities across the country, we have,

1304
01:47:30,169 --> 01:47:34,291
a methane digester system in Martinsville, Virginia.

1305
01:47:34,752 --> 01:47:38,454
We have solar gardens in Minnesota with Xcel Energy.

1306
01:47:38,474 --> 01:47:40,655
I personally worked on that project.

1307
01:47:40,995 --> 01:47:43,736
So we would be supportive of that.

1308
01:47:44,016 --> 01:47:47,278
Obviously it would be contingent upon the amount of investment.

1309
01:47:47,718 --> 01:47:48,859
it would take to do that.

1310
01:47:49,039 --> 01:48:06,528
And if that has an economic return, obviously, if it's a city ordinance or state law that we would have to comply with, we would ask that we'd be given the opportunity to review the regulations and the expected costs, but we're all, we are supportive of green energy.

1311
01:48:06,789 --> 01:48:07,149
So yes.

1312
01:48:07,935 --> 01:48:08,715
we're going to look at that.

1313
01:48:09,275 --> 01:48:10,456
But we have not today.

1314
01:48:11,136 --> 01:48:11,356
Okay.

1315
01:48:11,576 --> 01:48:11,936
Thank you.

1316
01:48:12,436 --> 01:48:18,998
And then my final question, if the chief of staff could confirm this, and I did, I had the opportunity to speak with Maria yesterday as well.

1317
01:48:19,778 --> 01:48:30,921
When presenting the benefit of this project tax-wise to the city, it is under the assumption that this benefit of $3 million is if no other company were to come in and not ask for a TIF, correct?

1318
01:48:30,941 --> 01:48:32,021
Correct.

1319
01:48:32,741 --> 01:48:32,961
Okay.

1320
01:48:33,201 --> 01:48:33,542
Thank you.

1321
01:48:33,942 --> 01:48:34,362
That's all I have.

1322
01:48:35,525 --> 01:48:36,586
Thank you, Councilor Morrell.

1323
01:48:36,947 --> 01:48:38,068
Vice President Carvio.

1324
01:48:38,168 --> 01:48:38,829
Thank you, Mr. President.

1325
01:48:38,849 --> 01:48:44,236
Thank you, Mr. Monica, for coming here and considering our community with your company.

1326
01:48:44,276 --> 01:48:50,944
Now, the $40 million you're talking about, that also includes the buying of the property, correct?

1327
01:48:51,144 --> 01:48:52,606
We are leasing the property.

1328
01:48:55,826 --> 01:48:58,508
Yeah, we're just going to be a tenant of the property.

1329
01:48:58,548 --> 01:49:06,792
It is owned by Medford Bakery Realty LLC is going to be the continued owner.

1330
01:49:06,812 --> 01:49:08,553
I believe they're the owner of record today.

1331
01:49:09,274 --> 01:49:10,695
And how long will you lease me for?

1332
01:49:10,715 --> 01:49:10,835
50 years.

1333
01:49:10,855 --> 01:49:10,875
5-0?

1334
01:49:16,055 --> 01:49:21,678
Yes, it's a 20-year lease with six five-year options.

1335
01:49:22,159 --> 01:49:28,042
So a 50-year commitment, which is very similar to the other commitments we have made in our other plants.

1336
01:49:28,082 --> 01:49:31,604
We're a long-term player in the food space.

1337
01:49:33,565 --> 01:49:42,590
And you did say you're only going to operate two shifts because I know Whole Foods, when they were in their bread and circus, they operated a 24-hour facility, correct?

1338
01:49:44,446 --> 01:49:47,747
And you're only going to operate two shifts, correct?

1339
01:49:49,048 --> 01:49:51,848
Our current plan is to operate two shifts.

1340
01:49:51,949 --> 01:49:57,890
As business volume needs dictated, we could go to a 24-7 operation.

1341
01:49:58,711 --> 01:50:04,113
But we would prefer to commit to what we can deliver and not over promise at this point.

1342
01:50:04,853 --> 01:50:07,414
And you mentioned about the jobs.

1343
01:50:07,694 --> 01:50:11,235
Are these union jobs or just jobs paid through your company?

1344
01:50:13,550 --> 01:50:15,813
They are not currently union jobs.

1345
01:50:17,034 --> 01:50:20,318
We do have union representation in our other plants.

1346
01:50:20,878 --> 01:50:21,659
Okay.

1347
01:50:21,839 --> 01:50:26,084
And how many trucks are you going to have at this facility?

1348
01:50:27,965 --> 01:50:34,312
Well, by trucks, do you mean trucks that monogram gourmet foods would operate?

1349
01:50:34,592 --> 01:50:34,833
Yes.

1350
01:50:35,855 --> 01:50:36,855
Yeah.

1351
01:50:37,475 --> 01:50:42,997
That's to be determined, but I would estimate that we'll probably operate three transfer trucks.

1352
01:50:44,257 --> 01:50:50,239
The finished product produced there, there is a small freezer, about 1300 pallet locations.

1353
01:50:50,739 --> 01:50:55,920
Our customers normally pick up at our plant and they use common carriers in most cases.

1354
01:50:55,960 --> 01:51:03,082
So there, our own assets would probably be three to four trucks to move ingredients between our warehouses.

1355
01:51:03,642 --> 01:51:05,804
and our other plants into here and out of there.

1356
01:51:05,904 --> 01:51:13,010
We currently ship a lot of our products out of a cold storage, public cold storage located down in Taunton.

1357
01:51:13,030 --> 01:51:16,213
Okay, and will those trucks be registered here in Medford?

1358
01:51:17,691 --> 01:51:22,914
Yes, they would be, and those would be part of the employment base of our employees.

1359
01:51:22,974 --> 01:51:29,838
And when I, I should clarify the $20 an hour wages, that's for the hourly production workers.

1360
01:51:29,919 --> 01:51:35,762
We would obviously have supervisors, managers, and a plant manager and a management team as well.

1361
01:51:35,862 --> 01:51:43,787
So there's a lot of, quite a few higher level paying jobs, management jobs within this plant facility.

1362
01:51:44,668 --> 01:51:46,289
And how many,

1363
01:51:47,512 --> 01:51:53,235
How many vehicles will be coming and going off the property during the working hours of the day?

1364
01:51:55,677 --> 01:52:09,985
Well, if we took the 250 employees and assumed that 80% of those were- Well, I mean, aside from the employees, I mean, commercial grade trucks coming in there.

1365
01:52:12,507 --> 01:52:13,568
How many commercial grade trucks?

1366
01:52:15,356 --> 01:52:17,158
That's a little hard to determine.

1367
01:52:17,218 --> 01:52:21,101
The facility we believe has operating flower silos.

1368
01:52:21,621 --> 01:52:24,524
So that cuts down the amount of dock unloading.

1369
01:52:24,584 --> 01:52:27,767
We'll be able to bulk fill the flower tanks and such.

1370
01:52:27,827 --> 01:52:40,858
So I'm going to guess, I'm going to estimate maybe three to four trucks a day unloading materials, finished goods, probably three to four, maybe as many as six picking up product a day, finished goods.

1371
01:52:42,091 --> 01:52:43,872
It seems to be less than we were doing there before.

1372
01:52:44,392 --> 01:52:47,914
And again, I want to thank the mayor for bringing this forward.

1373
01:52:47,954 --> 01:52:52,497
I think projects like this are always good for the community to hear about them.

1374
01:52:52,557 --> 01:52:57,499
And it's a good private-public partnership.

1375
01:52:58,080 --> 01:53:01,982
So I look forward to possibly having you in our community.

1376
01:53:03,775 --> 01:53:06,677
If I could add one more comment, I forgot to mention.

1377
01:53:07,237 --> 01:53:15,341
One of the other things that Monogram Foods does, we believe in giving back to our communities where we have plants and employees.

1378
01:53:15,401 --> 01:53:22,465
And we have a charitable 501C3 Monogram Loves Kids Foundation, which is independent of the company.

1379
01:53:23,065 --> 01:53:31,610
And last year we gave almost $600,000 worth of grants to our six different communities, cities where we have plants.

1380
01:53:32,210 --> 01:53:40,836
And those funds or grants are given to organizations to support children, whether it's the boys and girls clubs, a variety of things.

1381
01:53:41,016 --> 01:53:49,022
And the decisions of where that money is given back to the community of Medford would be made by the local management staff.

1382
01:53:49,142 --> 01:53:51,944
None of us in Memphis have any say over that.

1383
01:53:52,024 --> 01:53:54,546
So we want to be an employer of choice.

1384
01:53:55,086 --> 01:53:56,948
We want to be a good corporate citizen.

1385
01:53:57,648 --> 01:54:02,411
And we want to support the community, the children of the community, where that makes sense.

1386
01:54:02,471 --> 01:54:05,574
So that's part of the culture of Monogram Foods.

1387
01:54:05,634 --> 01:54:07,695
We are a rapidly growing company.

1388
01:54:08,195 --> 01:54:15,120
The plant in Wilmington, when we bought it five years ago, was doing $25 million in revenue.

1389
01:54:15,300 --> 01:54:19,803
This year, it will do over $150 million in revenue.

1390
01:54:19,863 --> 01:54:21,665
So we have the opportunity to grow.

1391
01:54:22,425 --> 01:54:29,489
And we are thankful that Medford is considering supporting us and our growth in your fine city, so.

1392
01:54:30,149 --> 01:54:35,112
Thank you, and I appreciate the fact that you're looking to be a good neighbor and contribute to the community.

1393
01:54:36,233 --> 01:54:37,513
Thank you, Vice President Carvio.

1394
01:54:37,553 --> 01:54:38,194
Councilor Marks.

1395
01:54:40,335 --> 01:54:42,816
Thank you, Mr. President, and I want to thank the

1396
01:54:44,845 --> 01:54:50,267
Mr. President, I have a few questions on the same line as Councilor Caviello.

1397
01:54:51,388 --> 01:54:59,911
Can you get a little more specific on the types of trucks that will be entering and exiting your particular facility?

1398
01:55:00,472 --> 01:55:01,932
Are we looking at 18 wheelers?

1399
01:55:02,392 --> 01:55:04,093
Are we looking at refrigerated trucks?

1400
01:55:04,553 --> 01:55:05,694
What type of truck?

1401
01:55:07,469 --> 01:55:15,699
It would be a traditional Class 8 semi-tractor, most likely 53-foot refrigerated trailers.

1402
01:55:15,759 --> 01:55:21,786
The majority of the bakery products are produced and shipped frozen.

1403
01:55:22,427 --> 01:55:30,614
So reefer trailers, we anticipate live loading, which means we will load that trailer, they'll back up, we load it and they leave.

1404
01:55:30,674 --> 01:55:34,657
We're not going to be leaving trailers idling on the lot.

1405
01:55:34,797 --> 01:55:39,261
As I said earlier, we're not a noisy business from that perspective.

1406
01:55:39,981 --> 01:55:48,388
We have a 1300 pallet freezer that's inside the building that if we retrofit it, should meet our needs for inside storage.

1407
01:55:49,125 --> 01:55:53,726
So class eight tractors, 53 foot trailers are the equipment.

1408
01:55:54,906 --> 01:56:02,167
Okay, and you're aware that you have residential neighbors on both sides, correct?

1409
01:56:03,527 --> 01:56:03,788
Yes.

1410
01:56:04,728 --> 01:56:18,290
Okay, and regarding your plant that after full build out, compared to what's there currently, how much more manufacturing will be done on that site?

1411
01:56:20,390 --> 01:56:21,874
I don't have, yeah.

1412
01:56:22,656 --> 01:56:24,541
Could you give us a rough percentage?

1413
01:56:26,304 --> 01:56:30,325
I don't have, I don't know how much business Whole Foods was doing out of there.

1414
01:56:30,345 --> 01:56:33,286
We're not privy to that confidential information.

1415
01:56:34,247 --> 01:56:38,688
I can tell you that, and our revenue is we're a privately held company.

1416
01:56:39,088 --> 01:56:46,230
So I would tell you we're going to be producing probably more poundage, more annual poundage than was produced before.

1417
01:56:46,250 --> 01:56:49,532
I don't know why Whole Foods closed that bakery down.

1418
01:56:49,792 --> 01:56:53,693
It was part of the Amazon acquisition is what I believe we heard.

1419
01:56:54,153 --> 01:57:03,337
through the trade industry, so I would anticipate us to be producing more annual pounds once we're up to full speed than was previously produced there.

1420
01:57:04,178 --> 01:57:08,420
Okay, and did you state that you do both retail and wholesale?

1421
01:57:10,233 --> 01:57:13,095
Yeah, well, I would say we do retail food service.

1422
01:57:14,377 --> 01:57:18,000
Some of our largest customers are large consumer.

1423
01:57:18,100 --> 01:57:20,282
We produce products for ConAgra Foods.

1424
01:57:20,842 --> 01:57:26,587
We produce products in Wilmington for B&G Foods, which is the Green Giant brand.

1425
01:57:27,007 --> 01:57:34,493
If you've ever had their, or your children have had their breaded vegetables, cauliflower and broccoli, we produce that product in Wilmington.

1426
01:57:34,513 --> 01:57:39,097
So both food service and retail grocery, we are not a branded company.

1427
01:57:39,137 --> 01:57:43,180
You will not find Monogram branded foods in your local grocery store.

1428
01:57:45,097 --> 01:57:48,819
Okay, so regarding, get back to the trucks.

1429
01:57:50,480 --> 01:57:57,063
Are you aware that there are many surrounding roads where you're located that do not accept heavy trucking?

1430
01:58:00,435 --> 01:58:05,459
Well, we are aware that there are streets that do have weight restrictions.

1431
01:58:06,600 --> 01:58:11,704
I guess I'll have to defer to our operations team and we can look further into that.

1432
01:58:11,744 --> 01:58:18,170
Were there problems in the past with ingress and egress of trucks into the site when it was Whole Foods Bakery?

1433
01:58:18,742 --> 01:58:28,408
Well, that's a tough question to answer because as you just alluded to, you're not sure what the older capacity was at the existing site.

1434
01:58:29,209 --> 01:58:31,830
And it seems like you're going to be growing the site.

1435
01:58:32,571 --> 01:58:35,633
And I could just tell you from a first hand experience that

1436
01:58:36,353 --> 01:58:40,636
The Felsway, many of your class A trucks cannot use the Felsway.

1437
01:58:41,117 --> 01:58:43,138
They cannot use Mystic Valley Parkway.

1438
01:58:43,899 --> 01:58:52,265
And I would be very curious to see if this work has been done ahead of time to see what the potential truck routes would be.

1439
01:58:53,385 --> 01:58:56,609
Because in my opinion, they would be cutting through many neighborhoods.

1440
01:58:57,370 --> 01:59:05,738
And I think that's extremely important for us to know, as a council, the impact this may have on surrounding neighbors.

1441
01:59:06,539 --> 01:59:09,462
And that leads to my other point that

1442
01:59:11,363 --> 01:59:17,685
I think, Mr. President, before we move forward with this, this would require community input.

1443
01:59:17,785 --> 01:59:21,327
And I realize this is a council meeting and it's open to the public.

1444
01:59:21,807 --> 01:59:24,548
However, it's the first time it's appeared on the agenda.

1445
01:59:25,108 --> 01:59:34,431
And I think the neighborhood where this is, I realized there was a baking facility there on a smaller scale.

1446
01:59:35,691 --> 01:59:39,893
I think this is going to have a much larger impact on the Wellington area.

1447
01:59:40,615 --> 01:59:41,664
And, you know.

1448
01:59:42,947 --> 01:59:45,028
Haines Square and so forth, Mr. President.

1449
01:59:45,468 --> 02:00:00,320
So I would ask that we have a public meeting on this where we invite the Wellington, Haines Square area, Mr. President, and notify them of what is taking place to see if residents would have any particular questions.

1450
02:00:01,580 --> 02:00:09,666
There's a host of questions that I rather do in committee of the whole regarding, I could just tell you first hand, I go to that Wendy's.

1451
02:00:11,366 --> 02:00:13,608
I hate to say it, quite often.

1452
02:00:14,929 --> 02:00:20,273
And I can tell you at night, Mr. President, that the rats are rampant in that back area.

1453
02:00:20,934 --> 02:00:25,177
If you want to check out rats, go by the back of the Wendy's.

1454
02:00:25,898 --> 02:00:34,825
And so there's a lot of issues regarding, and I'm sure these are addressed by the company, but there are a lot of issues I'm sure residents are going to have.

1455
02:00:35,126 --> 02:00:38,428
I know my colleagues already asked about odor and smell and so forth.

1456
02:00:38,809 --> 02:00:40,210
We've had a number of issues.

1457
02:00:40,910 --> 02:00:44,071
Mr. President, with docking stations.

1458
02:00:44,911 --> 02:00:50,613
We've experienced them in Salt Method with the Dunkin' Donuts that has a distributor off of Mystic Ave.

1459
02:00:51,253 --> 02:01:01,997
And even though businesses say they're quiet, when you take pallets to and from the trucks, especially if they're outdoor docking stations, that noise travels.

1460
02:01:02,597 --> 02:01:09,183
And as you know, we just built 145 condos behind the Wendy's in that particular area.

1461
02:01:09,504 --> 02:01:17,951
We have residents off to the left, which is right next to BJ, which is probably 100, 200 yards away, a couple hundred yards away.

1462
02:01:18,412 --> 02:01:24,458
So there's definitely a neighborhood in that area, Mr. President, and I would ask that we set up a committee of whole.

1463
02:01:25,158 --> 02:01:38,065
or if we want to have a next council meeting, serve as a public meeting to invite the neighborhood, Mr. President, and area residents so they can have input and see this presentation and ask questions.

1464
02:01:39,128 --> 02:01:48,310
And I appreciate also the fact that the administration is looking into bringing in additional businesses in our community.

1465
02:01:48,650 --> 02:01:54,552
I've always stated the Office of Community Development is supposed to be out there soliciting new businesses into the community.

1466
02:01:54,972 --> 02:01:56,792
So a TIF is another way.

1467
02:01:57,172 --> 02:02:00,633
Would I rather do it differently and not give any incentive?

1468
02:02:00,713 --> 02:02:07,975
And I probably would prefer that, Mr. President, but that remains a vote of this council and to see how this works.

1469
02:02:09,795 --> 02:02:20,199
So far, the last TIF I voted for, which was the sausage establishment on 9th Street, seems to be running very successful.

1470
02:02:20,519 --> 02:02:21,339
They're a good neighbor.

1471
02:02:21,659 --> 02:02:29,942
They're located within a residential area, but there were a lot of issues on that TIF that we had to work out, Mr. President.

1472
02:02:30,262 --> 02:02:37,585
A lot of neighborhood issues, as this gentleman mentioned, with the silos, noise, trucking, trucks that are idling.

1473
02:02:38,365 --> 02:02:39,767
It always happens, Mr. President.

1474
02:02:40,047 --> 02:02:45,572
The BJ parking lot, which is a giant parking lot right next to this building, go there at night.

1475
02:02:45,632 --> 02:02:48,795
There's 18 wheelers idling there at night, Mr. President.

1476
02:02:49,056 --> 02:02:52,599
Maybe not trying to get it to BJ's, but just a place to stay.

1477
02:02:52,659 --> 02:02:57,344
Also, Mr. President, the city just approved a gas station for the BJ's parking lot.

1478
02:02:57,784 --> 02:03:07,630
So we're going to add a brand new gas station with, I believe, eight pumps located right in the frontage on Middlesex Ave of a new gas station there.

1479
02:03:08,051 --> 02:03:10,372
So there's a lot going on in this area, Mr. President.

1480
02:03:10,752 --> 02:03:14,855
And to be quite frank, Middlesex Ave is deplorable.

1481
02:03:16,296 --> 02:03:19,938
The sidewalks, the street, it looks like a third world country.

1482
02:03:20,639 --> 02:03:21,219
It really does.

1483
02:03:21,579 --> 02:03:25,302
It's deplorable, it's a state owned road, it gets zero attention.

1484
02:03:26,337 --> 02:03:29,722
from the state, and Natural History City has zero responsibility.

1485
02:03:30,322 --> 02:03:41,077
So if we do move forward, Mr. President, and the TIF is with the state and so forth, I'd like to see a commitment from the state to do some work, Mr. President, on Middlesex Ave.

1486
02:03:42,118 --> 02:03:53,484
And bring it up to the 21st century regarding crossings, pedestrian safety, cars, and everything else, Mr. President, bike lanes, and everything else that needs to take place on Middlesex Ave.

1487
02:03:53,524 --> 02:03:57,085
So I would ask that, Mr. President, I am not going to vote on this tonight.

1488
02:03:57,446 --> 02:03:58,906
That doesn't mean I don't support it.

1489
02:03:59,447 --> 02:04:09,392
I want neighborhood input and I want the questions to be asked about the roadway and neighborhood concerns addressed.

1490
02:04:09,712 --> 02:04:10,012
Thank you.

1491
02:04:10,512 --> 02:04:11,573
Thank you, Councilor Marks.

1492
02:04:11,973 --> 02:04:12,533
Councilor Knight.

1493
02:04:14,394 --> 02:04:15,495
Thank you very much, Mr. President.

1494
02:04:16,716 --> 02:04:20,358
It appears to me that this would be what's classified as a bakery wholesaler.

1495
02:04:20,638 --> 02:04:23,320
Am I correct in making that assumption?

1496
02:04:25,141 --> 02:04:26,722
Mr. Monaco, would you be able to answer that?

1497
02:04:27,940 --> 02:04:36,548
Yeah, we would be a producer of bakery products for both wholesale and food service and retail.

1498
02:04:36,748 --> 02:04:41,792
So wholesalers end up delivering it to retailers in the end.

1499
02:04:41,872 --> 02:04:44,514
So yes, sir, I can live with that definition.

1500
02:04:44,995 --> 02:04:48,358
And in this Commonwealth of Massachusetts, I do believe that.

1501
02:04:49,317 --> 02:04:58,606
Because you'd be considered a bakery wholesaler and you'd be subject to USDA approval and inspection, you wouldn't be subject to the authority of the local board of health, is that correct?

1502
02:04:59,386 --> 02:05:00,087
That is correct.

1503
02:05:00,127 --> 02:05:07,354
As I stated earlier, this would be a USDA federally inspected bakery under all regulations.

1504
02:05:08,760 --> 02:05:08,940
Okay.

1505
02:05:10,241 --> 02:05:15,045
And we talked a little bit about the jobs that Monogram's going to bring.

1506
02:05:15,065 --> 02:05:20,468
And I'm relatively familiar with Monogram Foods from my day job working in the insurance industry.

1507
02:05:20,609 --> 02:05:25,452
And I understand a lot of these positions are packaging jobs and manufacturing almost type jobs?

1508
02:05:27,674 --> 02:05:27,914
Yes.

1509
02:05:28,815 --> 02:05:36,160
And then you'd have also a smaller array of positions that were mid to upper level management and then you'd have some drivers?

1510
02:05:37,928 --> 02:05:49,157
Quality assurance people, supervisors, financial accounting people, general plant management, drivers, warehouse men, yes.

1511
02:05:50,358 --> 02:05:54,061
And is there any local hiring preference that's part of the TIF?

1512
02:05:55,302 --> 02:06:02,047
I'm sorry, any local- Local hiring, if you're located in Medford and you have two applicants, and one of them's from Medford and one of them's from Everett.

1513
02:06:03,142 --> 02:06:04,983
Does the Medford person get the job?

1514
02:06:05,043 --> 02:06:06,845
Is there a local hiring preference?

1515
02:06:06,965 --> 02:06:17,672
Our plan is to give Medford, experienced Medford employees, those that particularly have bakery experience, that's of great interest to us.

1516
02:06:18,693 --> 02:06:21,115
As you covered earlier on your other topics,

1517
02:06:21,915 --> 02:06:27,180
employees in your particular area of greater Boston, proximity to work is important.

1518
02:06:27,220 --> 02:06:28,582
The commutes can be terrible.

1519
02:06:28,662 --> 02:06:34,567
So we're hopeful there's a good pool of applicants within the greater Medford City area that will work for us.

1520
02:06:36,028 --> 02:06:37,149
And there is a Medford hiring.

1521
02:06:37,189 --> 02:06:39,271
There is a Medford provision built within the agreement.

1522
02:06:39,532 --> 02:06:39,832
There is.

1523
02:06:39,872 --> 02:06:40,252
Awesome.

1524
02:06:40,352 --> 02:06:40,553
Awesome.

1525
02:06:40,573 --> 02:06:40,733
Great.

1526
02:06:40,753 --> 02:06:41,173
Thanks, Dave.

1527
02:06:41,754 --> 02:06:42,114
It's in there.

1528
02:06:43,535 --> 02:06:43,755
OK.

1529
02:06:45,517 --> 02:06:45,737
Well.

1530
02:06:47,077 --> 02:06:49,982
I personally have supported tips in the past.

1531
02:06:50,042 --> 02:06:54,410
I think that it's a great way to jumpstart our economy and bring jobs to the community.

1532
02:06:55,612 --> 02:06:58,877
The jobs that pay $20 an hour, the jobs that pay $800 a week.

1533
02:07:00,987 --> 02:07:02,909
Those aren't necessarily the jobs I'm crazy about.

1534
02:07:03,310 --> 02:07:07,274
I'd like to see jobs that pay a living wage so the people that work here can live here.

1535
02:07:07,414 --> 02:07:11,619
And that hiring preference isn't going to go too far if the people working there are going to make 800 bucks a week.

1536
02:07:12,439 --> 02:07:17,405
With that being said, there are other positions and other jobs and other benefits that come with having an employer of this size in the community.

1537
02:07:18,045 --> 02:07:19,346
But I would agree with Councilor Mox.

1538
02:07:19,386 --> 02:07:29,069
In the past when we've done this, we've taken a slow and deliberate approach to be sure that we don't all arise cross LRTs and also listen to the concerns that the residents have.

1539
02:07:29,970 --> 02:07:35,472
In looking at the location of this facility, it's, I believe, located in an industrially zoned district.

1540
02:07:36,212 --> 02:07:38,633
a wholesale bakery can be stationed there by right.

1541
02:07:39,834 --> 02:07:45,576
The option, the ability for the council to bring this entity to the table right now is purely based around this TIF.

1542
02:07:46,497 --> 02:07:55,661
So I think it would be a good exercise for us to allow the opportunity to entertain Councilor Mark's motion, and I would second it or support it if he offers it.

1543
02:07:56,281 --> 02:08:05,505
And move from there, but this is something that historically I've supported, and I certainly see no problem with it based upon the preliminary presentation that's been made, but I would like to hear from the residents as well.

1544
02:08:06,127 --> 02:08:06,928
Thank you, Councilor Knight.

1545
02:08:07,008 --> 02:08:09,849
On the motion of Councilor Marks, seconded by Councilor Knight, Councilor Beers.

1546
02:08:12,211 --> 02:08:13,151
Thank you, Mr. President.

1547
02:08:14,212 --> 02:08:17,254
You know, I've done a dive on this, done some research around TIFs.

1548
02:08:17,474 --> 02:08:19,815
I spoke with Maria from MOBD as well.

1549
02:08:21,737 --> 02:08:31,543
You know, and from what I've understood, these have been used as an incentive to address areas of low demand, areas of blight, kind of that's the intent here.

1550
02:08:33,535 --> 02:08:37,139
I wouldn't necessarily say that Medford is an area of low demand or an area of blight.

1551
02:08:37,539 --> 02:08:43,125
I know this has, you know, bakery has not been operated in for a little while, so there might be a little wiggle room there.

1552
02:08:43,205 --> 02:08:48,190
But, you know, that's one of the concerns I have.

1553
02:08:48,330 --> 02:08:55,077
And also in my research and speaking with MOBD, it does seem that tips are mostly going to large corporations versus

1554
02:08:56,300 --> 02:08:57,801
looking at small businesses.

1555
02:08:57,861 --> 02:09:02,162
So that's another area of concern that I have in general around the process.

1556
02:09:03,062 --> 02:09:08,384
I do have a couple questions for Mr. Monica from Monogram Foods.

1557
02:09:09,305 --> 02:09:18,768
The first of which is, have you discussed or would you consider any curbing, driveway, or traffic improvements around the property?

1558
02:09:22,071 --> 02:09:30,555
Would you be referring to on the actual property we would be leasing, or are you talking on city-owned property?

1559
02:09:30,575 --> 02:09:32,936
It seems to me it might even be state-owned property.

1560
02:09:34,337 --> 02:09:36,358
Essentially, I drive that road a lot.

1561
02:09:36,458 --> 02:09:37,959
It's not a very safe area.

1562
02:09:38,079 --> 02:09:41,720
I would expect that trucks are going to have some issues coming out of your location.

1563
02:09:41,740 --> 02:09:46,463
And during your study of this location as a potential location,

1564
02:09:47,403 --> 02:09:56,406
have you noticed or considered working with the state or the city around state-owned or city-owned property as well as your property?

1565
02:09:57,987 --> 02:09:58,747
Yes, we do.

1566
02:09:59,007 --> 02:10:14,652
Normally, as part of a plant remodel of this size, we would look at all ingresses and egresses, primarily from employee safety and where the employees would park, where trucks would come in and unload or back trailers in.

1567
02:10:14,672 --> 02:10:15,733
So, yes, we would look at that.

1568
02:10:15,793 --> 02:10:16,573
We'd be open to

1569
02:10:17,313 --> 02:10:22,696
improving curb cuts, making sure they were in the right locations and they were safe.

1570
02:10:22,816 --> 02:10:25,277
Obviously we can't have damaged equipment.

1571
02:10:25,297 --> 02:10:34,081
So if the facility's parking lot is in bad shape and has potholes, we're going to fix those things as part of our normal rehab of a facility.

1572
02:10:35,582 --> 02:10:35,822
Great.

1573
02:10:35,942 --> 02:10:36,403
Thank you.

1574
02:10:38,083 --> 02:10:45,207
Next question is, you know, are you considering any other locations for this plant other than Medford?

1575
02:10:47,472 --> 02:10:59,419
We have considered four alternative locations, two of which are in Massachusetts and two of which are not, are located in other states where we have plants.

1576
02:11:01,120 --> 02:11:03,321
So that's as much as I can say on that.

1577
02:11:04,542 --> 02:11:11,965
We have two substantial plants in Wisconsin and that was one of our other sites as well.

1578
02:11:12,045 --> 02:11:14,706
So yes, we went through a complete search.

1579
02:11:15,826 --> 02:11:18,487
I think the original list had eight potential sites.

1580
02:11:18,527 --> 02:11:19,748
We narrowed that down to four.

1581
02:11:20,868 --> 02:11:21,829
Okay, gotcha.

1582
02:11:21,909 --> 02:11:30,512
And I do have a few more questions, but I think on the note that Councilor Knight was sending and my fellow councilors as well, you know,

1583
02:11:31,182 --> 02:11:34,383
If we make a commitment to you, we'd want a shared commitment there.

1584
02:11:34,563 --> 02:11:38,365
So I do think that should be part of a deliberative process to move forward.

1585
02:11:39,786 --> 02:11:41,006
It sounded like you're privately held.

1586
02:11:41,026 --> 02:11:47,969
You might not be able or willing to answer this question, but what is Monogram's net revenue annually?

1587
02:11:51,901 --> 02:11:55,643
This year, it will approximate 750 million.

1588
02:11:56,243 --> 02:11:59,285
So I'm not sure what you consider to be a large company.

1589
02:12:00,045 --> 02:12:02,466
We are only 16 years old.

1590
02:12:03,087 --> 02:12:09,570
And so we're very proud of our growth, but we don't consider ourselves a large company at that revenue level.

1591
02:12:10,070 --> 02:12:10,410
Got it.

1592
02:12:10,810 --> 02:12:13,852
And that's just kind of goes to my next question, which is

1593
02:12:16,234 --> 02:12:19,956
Is $600,000 really going to be the difference for you?

1594
02:12:19,976 --> 02:12:28,359
I would consider you, maybe we'll call you medium-sized, but $750 million sounds like a lot of money to me.

1595
02:12:28,519 --> 02:12:42,644
Is this $600,000 really the difference maker for you in making this kind of long-term decision versus all of the other factors that you've mentioned, like the location and the building and the silos and all of the other conditions?

1596
02:12:42,704 --> 02:12:43,864
Is it really the $600,000 that's the make or break?

1597
02:12:47,462 --> 02:12:54,587
All state incentives and local TIF incentives are relevant to every decision that we make.

1598
02:12:55,428 --> 02:12:59,031
It's not the only decision, but in this case, it is a relevant decision.

1599
02:12:59,451 --> 02:13:05,455
As I said, we're not a large company, and between the real estate tax incentive

1600
02:13:07,177 --> 02:13:12,040
and the personal property, it's approximately, David can answer this, I think it was 950,000.

1601
02:13:12,721 --> 02:13:17,825
So it is material to our decision, yes.

1602
02:13:18,786 --> 02:13:19,366
Okay.

1603
02:13:19,787 --> 02:13:26,552
The 950,000 number that Jeff mentioned is what we view as the upper limit of what it would be.

1604
02:13:26,672 --> 02:13:32,137
So when I was talking about a TIF, there's always some flexibility, there's always some unknown variables.

1605
02:13:32,497 --> 02:13:33,578
So in the modeling that we did

1606
02:13:33,778 --> 02:13:36,341
that showed the $4 million net value back to the city.

1607
02:13:36,981 --> 02:13:44,588
The more Monogram invests, the more market forces impact the value, the larger the exemption, but also larger the revenue back to the city.

1608
02:13:44,749 --> 02:13:55,399
So there will be some fluctuation there, but based on Ellen's best guess and Ellen's hard work, I think that that number is exactly where, it's definitely gonna be in that window.

1609
02:13:56,478 --> 02:13:56,698
Right.

1610
02:13:57,058 --> 02:13:57,759
And I understand.

1611
02:13:57,839 --> 02:14:06,385
I'm just saying, you know, regardless 600,000 at the low end, 950 at the high end, we're talking about like 0.1% of the annual revenue for a 50 year investment.

1612
02:14:06,425 --> 02:14:20,355
It just, you know, it's a small relative to this amount that you mentioned of $750 million a year and that you're a quickly growing company and that you sextupled the amount of revenue that was coming from your plant in Wilmington.

1613
02:14:20,395 --> 02:14:25,038
You know, it's, it seems like in some sense in your account book, it might be,

1614
02:14:26,095 --> 02:14:27,456
worth a little bit less to you than to us.

1615
02:14:27,756 --> 02:14:32,799
Our revenue is not $750 million a year here in Medford.

1616
02:14:33,039 --> 02:14:35,720
And thank you for answering my questions.

1617
02:14:36,340 --> 02:14:49,447
I think maybe more directed towards Alicia Hunt or Dave Rodriguez, I do have some concerns that this sets a bad precedent, considering that we are a pretty high demand community.

1618
02:14:49,487 --> 02:14:50,748
Our property values are growing.

1619
02:14:50,768 --> 02:14:55,270
It seems that that's going to continue for the foreseeable future in the greater Boston area.

1620
02:14:56,093 --> 02:15:03,634
Do you have any concerns that this sets a precedent for offering public subsidies and discounts in order to get new businesses in the future after this project?

1621
02:15:05,430 --> 02:15:09,812
Well, I can't speak for and I think this is a good conversation for the mayor as well.

1622
02:15:09,832 --> 02:15:11,953
And I've always viewed TIFs as case by case.

1623
02:15:12,853 --> 02:15:14,894
So I don't view this as precedent setting.

1624
02:15:14,934 --> 02:15:23,237
I view this as looking at bringing this business to this location and for the city and the value that it provides to the city based on that analysis.

1625
02:15:23,677 --> 02:15:28,119
Every TIF is going to be case by case based upon some of the factors that you talked about.

1626
02:15:28,899 --> 02:15:42,025
So I'm not worried about creating a precedent because there is a strong check on this through the council process to say, you know, some cities and towns have given out TIFs pretty tightly.

1627
02:15:42,265 --> 02:15:43,886
Others have given it out pretty loosely.

1628
02:15:44,766 --> 02:15:53,290
So it's a case by, I've always viewed this as case by case, what's best for the community, for the business that they're bringing in and the site that they're being located at.

1629
02:15:53,330 --> 02:15:56,392
So I'll defer to Alicia as well as to her thoughts.

1630
02:15:56,992 --> 02:16:06,537
on that, but I'm not concerned about setting a precedent.

1631
02:16:06,597 --> 02:16:08,157
Is Alicia not my Alicia?

1632
02:16:09,838 --> 02:16:11,999
I have the wrong Alicia, sorry.

1633
02:16:12,139 --> 02:16:12,620
Alicia Hunt.

1634
02:16:14,908 --> 02:16:20,972
that we've been seeing is that Medford is a hot demand for residential.

1635
02:16:21,512 --> 02:16:29,117
And every developer that has been knocking on our door, almost every developer, has been wanting to build a large multifamily residence.

1636
02:16:29,717 --> 02:16:33,540
And that is something that has caused this council a lot of angst.

1637
02:16:33,560 --> 02:16:35,221
It's caused the mayor a lot of angst.

1638
02:16:35,941 --> 02:16:42,065
And one of the things we have been looking to do is to bring in more commercial entities that bring jobs with them.

1639
02:16:42,806 --> 02:16:45,249
and this business is bringing jobs.

1640
02:16:45,910 --> 02:16:49,895
I don't have another business knocking on the door saying, can we give you jobs?

1641
02:16:50,316 --> 02:16:57,746
We didn't make a big deal of it when Whole Foods closed last winter, but they did close and all of those people were laid off.

1642
02:16:58,408 --> 02:17:12,020
And this is somebody who actually wants to not just put another business there, but actually a business with the hopes of rehiring the people in this area who were recently laid off by that entity there.

1643
02:17:12,501 --> 02:17:14,763
They'll be bringing back similar jobs.

1644
02:17:14,943 --> 02:17:16,865
They'll be doing similar kinds of work.

1645
02:17:17,540 --> 02:17:22,341
it'll be no more disruption to the community than we had there previously.

1646
02:17:22,721 --> 02:17:30,943
We're hoping because it's a new business and we're having conversations with them, that disruption that notice would be less than what we had there.

1647
02:17:31,763 --> 02:17:39,465
But the basis, bottom line is, those people don't have jobs right now unless they've gone off and found them in other areas.

1648
02:17:40,086 --> 02:17:42,586
This is something that we would like to see here in the city.

1649
02:17:44,307 --> 02:17:45,907
I mean, I understand the idea of jobs,

1650
02:17:46,752 --> 02:17:54,073
And no disrespect, if it's been 11 months, I would guess that they've had to get another job at this point just to pay the rent.

1651
02:17:54,913 --> 02:18:02,935
I understand bringing in jobs, but to Councilor Knight's point as well, it might cost more than $20 an hour to live in Medford.

1652
02:18:02,955 --> 02:18:04,795
At least that's my personal experience.

1653
02:18:07,816 --> 02:18:16,057
I guess- We have a large number of people that actually make and live here that make below the area median income.

1654
02:18:17,377 --> 02:18:22,820
Our area median income is lower than the regional area median income.

1655
02:18:23,401 --> 02:18:25,322
So that is something to consider.

1656
02:18:25,382 --> 02:18:28,864
It is very expensive to live in Medford because of the housing prices.

1657
02:18:29,684 --> 02:18:33,407
But we've also been going through a pandemic and we have very high unemployment rates.

1658
02:18:33,867 --> 02:18:39,430
We're seeing unprecedented usage of the food pantries here in Medford.

1659
02:18:39,910 --> 02:18:46,194
So I would not assume that the people who were working there have found jobs.

1660
02:18:46,888 --> 02:18:48,969
that there's a high unemployment rate going on.

1661
02:18:49,389 --> 02:18:50,609
No, that wasn't what I was saying.

1662
02:18:50,629 --> 02:18:54,051
I was saying I assume they've had to find some way to make money in the interim period.

1663
02:18:54,091 --> 02:18:57,852
They're not just waiting for Monogram to move in here to take an old job back.

1664
02:18:59,593 --> 02:19:02,974
So, you know, I guess it sounds like it's case by case.

1665
02:19:03,034 --> 02:19:04,574
It's not setting a precedent.

1666
02:19:06,115 --> 02:19:08,075
At least that's the position of the administration.

1667
02:19:08,816 --> 02:19:10,436
And I understand all the other factors.

1668
02:19:11,177 --> 02:19:12,137
I do think it is a

1669
02:19:13,101 --> 02:19:20,049
of concern to set a precedent to say, if we want a business here, we're going to have to give them hundreds of thousands of dollars in tax breaks to do it.

1670
02:19:20,169 --> 02:19:25,455
So that's a concern that I have, in addition to the other concerns that have been raised by fellow councilors.

1671
02:19:25,976 --> 02:19:28,999
And I look forward to more deliberation on the matter.

1672
02:19:29,339 --> 02:19:30,340
Thank you, Mr. President.

1673
02:19:30,761 --> 02:19:31,862
Thank you, Councilor Behrs.

1674
02:19:31,942 --> 02:19:32,963
Point of information, Mr. President.

1675
02:19:34,040 --> 02:19:35,041
Point of information, Mr. President.

1676
02:19:35,061 --> 02:19:36,962
Point of information from the Vice President.

1677
02:19:37,683 --> 02:19:42,806
I've been on this council ten years, and this is only the second TIF that's come my way.

1678
02:19:42,906 --> 02:19:44,287
Council March has been here longer.

1679
02:19:44,747 --> 02:19:45,888
I don't know if anything has come.

1680
02:19:47,229 --> 02:19:51,532
So let's say, so TIF's not given up very generously in this community.

1681
02:19:52,292 --> 02:19:54,874
Let's say this is only the second one that I've been involved with in ten years.

1682
02:19:56,848 --> 02:20:05,710
And by the way, I think they're a useful tool to bring business to the community, especially where things are very competitive these days.

1683
02:20:05,730 --> 02:20:07,250
Thank you.

1684
02:20:07,270 --> 02:20:08,370
Thank you, Vice President Carriello.

1685
02:20:08,730 --> 02:20:10,591
Councilor Villescaz, I'll start with your question.

1686
02:20:11,331 --> 02:20:22,673
I would just add, just for the notes, for the record, for the future, that we look into using some of the proceeds if the TIF is approved,

1687
02:20:23,537 --> 02:20:35,382
into tip accountability that's been one of the recommendations, policy recommendations around tips recently, making sure that they are being held up, that the agreements are being held to.

1688
02:20:35,462 --> 02:20:40,084
So I'd just like to put that for the record, maybe for a future committee of the whole meeting to discuss further.

1689
02:20:41,185 --> 02:20:43,026
And I understand it's not something we've done in the past.

1690
02:20:43,066 --> 02:20:45,567
I'm more concerned about what we're going to do in the future.

1691
02:20:46,407 --> 02:20:47,708
We do have a new administration.

1692
02:20:47,728 --> 02:20:50,409
We're hiring economic development director.

1693
02:20:51,111 --> 02:20:56,854
Is this going to be our economic development plan going forward to bring in this business because we have this high residential demand?

1694
02:20:56,874 --> 02:20:58,594
So I understand we haven't done it in the past.

1695
02:20:58,654 --> 02:21:02,556
I think that's probably a good thing, good stewardship, that we're not just giving these out willy-nilly.

1696
02:21:02,616 --> 02:21:06,758
I know there are a lot of communities that do that and have found themselves in trouble.

1697
02:21:07,318 --> 02:21:12,201
City of Chicago, 33% of their property tax revenue is wrapped up in TIFs right now.

1698
02:21:12,261 --> 02:21:12,661
I know that's

1699
02:21:13,225 --> 02:21:19,470
A little different from Medford, but I also know Malden, Salem, and other communities have used these tools pretty extensively.

1700
02:21:20,631 --> 02:21:24,453
So just saying we need to keep a close eye on the future.

1701
